<header class="header">
  <h1>How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Short seasons require climate-based precision.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    But in short-season climates, the real constraint is not just when frost begins and ends —
    it is how much heat accumulates before frost returns.
  </p>
  <p>
    Many short-season gardens fail not because frost arrives “too early,” but because crops never accumulate enough seasonal heat to reach maturity before the frost boundary.
    Planning must move beyond calendar assumptions and toward climate-based modeling.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Counts as a Short Growing Season?</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are framed using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    These boundaries represent what typically happens — not a guarantee in any given year.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short growing season generally means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>An earlier-than-average first fall frost</li>
    <li>Cool early spring and late fall temperatures</li>
    <li>Lower total accumulated Growing Degree Days (GDD)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can determine your local frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone do not determine crop success.
    Two locations may both report 110 frost-free days — yet produce very different harvest outcomes because their seasonal heat accumulation differs.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Real Constraint: The Frost Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    A growing season is bounded by two frost events at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Last spring frost</li>
    <li>First fall frost</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    At the 50% probability level, these dates represent the midpoint of historical outcomes.
    Roughly half of years will experience frost earlier or later than these listed boundaries.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short-season climates, the window between these frost boundaries is compressed.
    More importantly, the <strong>usable heat inside that window</strong> is often limited.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Calendar Logic Fails in Short Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    Seed packets often list “days to maturity.”
    In a 100-day frost-free season, a 95-day crop may appear safe.
  </p>

  <p>
    But days-to-maturity assumes average warmth.
    If temperatures remain cool, the crop may accumulate heat too slowly and reach the frost boundary before physiological maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    For example:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>A tomato labeled 95 days may require roughly 1,600–1,800 GDD (base 50°F).</li>
    <li>If your season only accumulates 1,500 GDD before first frost, the crop operates at a heat deficit.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Even though the calendar window appears sufficient, the seasonal heat budget is not.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is explained further in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Your Seasonal Heat Budget (Growing Degree Days)</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days measure accumulated heat over time.
    Most warm-season crops use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day contributes heat units when average temperature exceeds 50°F.
    Over the frost-free window, those units accumulate into your
    <strong>seasonal heat budget</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how many GDD typically accumulate before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a deeper system explanation, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Evaluating Crop Feasibility by Heat Demand</h2>

  <p>
    Once you know your seasonal heat budget, compare it to crop requirements.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Low heat demand:</strong> Often under ~1,200 GDD (lettuce, spinach, radishes)</li>
    <li><strong>Moderate heat demand:</strong> ~1,200–1,800 GDD (bush beans, zucchini)</li>
    <li><strong>High heat demand:</strong> 2,000+ GDD (large tomatoes, winter squash, long-season sweet corn)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Within each category, variety differences are substantial.
    For example, tomato cultivars can range from roughly 1,200 to over 2,000 GDD.
    See
    <a href="/guides/how-many-growing-degree-days-do-tomatoes-need/">How Many Growing Degree Days Do Tomatoes Need?</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your expected seasonal GDD comfortably exceeds a crop’s requirement, maturity is likely in a typical year.
    If your seasonal GDD barely matches the requirement, you are operating near the frost boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin: Comfortable, Borderline, or Unlikely</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD exceeds crop requirement by several hundred units.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD closely matches requirement.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely Margin:</strong> Seasonal GDD typically falls short.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because frost dates use probability framing, year-to-year variation affects outcomes.
    Borderline crops may mature in warmer-than-typical years and fail in cooler ones.
  </p>

  <p>
    Planning is not about eliminating risk —
    it is about intentionally choosing your margin relative to the frost boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Applied Scenario Modeling</h2>

  <p><strong>Scenario 1 — 2,200 GDD Available</strong><br>
  A 1,300 GDD tomato has strong margin.<br>
  A 2,100 GDD heirloom operates near the frost boundary.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario 2 — 1,800 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Short-season sweet corn (~1,500 GDD) may mature.<br>
  Winter squash requiring 2,200+ GDD becomes unlikely.</p>

  <p><strong>Scenario 3 — 1,400 GDD Available</strong><br>
  Cool-season crops thrive.<br>
  High-heat crops are structurally mismatched to the climate.</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Can Season Extension Increase Your Heat Budget?</h2>

  <p>
    Techniques like indoor seed starting, row covers, and warm microclimates can reduce frost exposure risk.
    You can coordinate transplant timing using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, season extension primarily protects against frost.
    It does <strong>not materially increase cumulative seasonal GDD</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Protection can improve risk margin.
    It cannot transform a low-heat climate into a high-heat one.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Short-Season Planning Model</h2>

  <p>
    Effective planning follows a clear sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost → Season Length → Growing Degree Days → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    Step 1: Identify frost boundaries at 32°F (50% probability).<br>
    Step 2: Define your frost-free window.<br>
    Step 3: Estimate seasonal GDD before first frost.<br>
    Step 4: Compare crop heat requirements to your heat budget.<br>
    Step 5: Evaluate your margin.
  </p>

  <p>
    When these elements align, crop maturity becomes predictable in a typical year.
    When they do not, calendar-based advice often fails.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short seasons are constrained by frost timing and limited heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Frost boundaries use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days define your seasonal heat budget.</li>
    <li>Crop viability depends on whether your heat budget exceeds crop requirements.</li>
    <li>Risk margin determines predictability near the frost boundary.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, successful planning comes from modeling frost boundaries and heat accumulation together —
    not relying on planting calendars alone.
  </p>
</section>